etymologies: late Middle English; earliest use found in Abbey Holy Ghost. From Anglo-Norman and Middle French chanteresse, feminine form corresponding to Anglo-Norman chantre, chanteor, chanteour, Middle French chanteur

definitions: A female chanter or singer; specifically a female cantor or precentor (now chiefly historical). Formerly also: †a song bird (obsolete).

etymologies: late Middle English; earliest use found in John Lydgate (c1370–c1449), poet and prior of Hatfield Regis. Shortened from enchantress

definitions: A female magician; a sorceress, an enchantress.
